This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it evaluates the performance of a learning algorithm for ranked retrieval in web search. Additionally, the paper draws upon user studies in laboratory and real-world settings, which suggests that it may also belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of a model to understand user behavior, which could place it in the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category. The evaluation of the algorithm's effectiveness suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the exploration of a wide range of possible user behaviors could place it in the Cybernetics (cs.CY) sub-category.
